Here's a simple function that uses a Markdown parser library called `pugcpp` to convert Markdown to HTML. You'll need to install `pugcpp` using your package manager or by cloning the repository and building it yourself.

Please note that you'll also need to include the necessary headers and link against the library.

```cpp
#include <pugcpp/v1/markdown/doc.hpp>
#include <pugcpp/v1/html/html.hpp>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugcpp::markdown::parser md;
    pugcpp::html::parser html;
    std::string htmlText;
    pugcpp::html::node htmlNode;

    try {
        htmlNode = md.parse(markdown);
        htmlText = html.render(htmlNode);
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        // Handle the exception
        return "";
    }

    return htmlText;
}
```

If you don't want to use an external library, you could implement a simple Markdown parser yourself, but that would be a significant undertaking. Markdown is a superset of standard text, and it has many edge cases and subtleties. Here's a very basic example of a Markdown parser that supports only a few features:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("#([^\n]+)\n"), "<h1>$1</h1>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("##([^\n]+)\n"), "<h2>$1</h2>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("###([^\n]+)\n"), "<h3>$1</h3>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("([^\n]*)\n\n", std::regex::format_first_only), "<p>$1</p>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("([*\-+]) [^\n]+\n", std::regex::format_first_only), "<ul><li>$0</li></ul>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("    ([^\n]+)\n", std::regex::format_first_only), "<pre><code>$1</code></pre>");
    return html;
}
```

This function only supports headers, paragraphs, unordered lists, and code blocks. It's not even close to a full Markdown parser, but it should give you an idea of how you could approach this task.

In a real-world application, you'd want to use a well-maintained, battle-tested Markdown parser library.

